k includes one of the first biographical portraits of Teresa and Maria's personal account of the troubled founding of the Discalced convent at Seville, as well as her tribulations as an Inquisitional suspect. Rich in allusions to women's affective relationships in the early modern convent, Book for the Hour of Recreation also serves as an example of how a woman might write when relatively free of clerical censorship and expectations. A detailed introduction and notes by Alison Weber provide historical and biographical context for Amanda Powell's fluid translation.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aChristian saintszSpainzAvilavBiography. 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / General.2bisacsh  ateresa of avila, maria de san jose salazar, carmelite nun, reform, religion, spirituality, catholicism, prioress, convent, seclusion, nunnery, seville, lisbon, spain, history, catholic reformation, gender, women in the church, leadership, education, discalced, music, plays, drama, faith, belief, worship, piety, religious experience, nonfiction, recreation, spiritual teaching, inquisition, affect, female friendship, saints, art.1 aKing, Margaret L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPowell, Amanda, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRabil, Albert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWeber, Alison, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWeber, Alison, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z97831106353860 cprintz978022673454540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226734620423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226734620/original  a978-3-11-063538-6  Uni